04290nam a22007695i 9783110924404DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20121999gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831109244047 a10.1515/97831109244042doi  a(DE-B1597)45774  a(OCoLC)1004880248  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPE3726b.G688 1999eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a427/.09222  aHF 1512rvk0(DE-625)rvk/48774:1 aGotti, Maurizio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Language of Thieves and Vagabonds :b17th and 18th Century Canting Lexicography in England /cMaurizio Gotti.  aReprint 2012 1aTübingen : bMax Niemeyer Verlag, c[2012] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (159 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLexicographica. Series Maior : Supplementbände zum Internationalen Jahrbuch für Lexikographie ,x0175-9264 ;v940 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe object of the volume is the analysis of the main dictionaries and glossaries of the canting language (the particular jargon spoken by thieves and vagabonds) that appeared in the 17th and 18th centuries. The scholars' attention has mostly concentrated on the earliest publications - particulary those appearing in the Elizabethan period -, while relatively little research has investigated subsequent canting dictionaries and glossaries. The aim of the present volume is to fill this gap. The main works on canting published in the 17th and 18th centuries are analysed in chapters 3 to 10. The first two chapters provide a necessary introduction to the investigation carried out in the subsequent sections, examining the great increase in the numbers of vagabonds and criminals in England in that period from a sociohistorical perspective and reviewing the 16th-century English literature about the underworld. The subsequent eight chapters give a detailed analysis of the main works on canting which appeared in the second part of the 17th century and during the whole of the 18th century. The specific features of each publication are identified, as well as the method adopted by its author in the compilation of his dictionary/glossary and the most likely sources of its entries, in order to determine the degree of novelty and relevance that his contribution has brought to this field. The final chapter deals with the evolution in the meaning of the term 'cant' itself in the period taken into consideration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aCanty17th century. 0aCanty18th century. 0aFlash (Prisoners' dialect). 0aThieveszEnglandxLanguagexHistory. 4aEnglisch. 4aGaunersprache. 4aGeschichte 1676-1785. 4aLexikographie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 1990 - 1999z9783110636895oZDB-23-DLS0 cprintz978348430994440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311092440440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110924404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110924404/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DLSc1990d1999